ustralianempire.webs.com/ \"The Australian Empire\"] by Rob Robinson, 2009\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080903131313/http://www.sl.nsw.gov.au/discover_collections/history_nation/terra_australis/index.html From Terra Australis to Australia], State Library of New South Wales\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110216230554/http://www.cultureandrecreation.gov.au/articles/australianhistory/ European discovery and the colonisation of Australia \u2013 Australian Government]\n* [http://www.abc.net.au/local/audio/2010/05/14/2899543.htm Looking For Blackfellas Point] History of European settlement and relations with Aboriginal people of South Eastern Australia, Australian Broadcasting Corporation\n* [http://www.rahs.org.au Royal Australian Historical Society]\n\n{{Australia topic|title=History of Australia|prefix=History of|VI=Victoria}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list ={{History by continent}}\n{{History of Oceania}}\n{{Coord|25|21|S|131|14|E|source:ruwiki|display=title}}\n}}\n\n{{Australia topics}}\n{{Convicts in Australia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:History Of Australia}}\n[[Category:History of Australia| ]]\n", "name_user": "203.220.154.161", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Australia"}
{"title_page": "Integral Coach Factory", "text_new": "{{Short description|A production unit under Ministry of Railways (India)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Integral Coach Factory\n| logo = \n| type = [[Government]]\n| industry = [[Rail transport]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1955|10|02}}\n| hq_location = [[Chennai]], [[Tamilnadu]], [[India]] \n| area_served = [[Asia-Pacific]] <br /> [[Africa]]\n| key_people = Rahul Jain <br /> (General Manager)\n| products = [[Rolling stock]] <br /> [[Electric multiple unit|EMU]] <br /> [[MEMU]]\n| production = 3262 coaches (2018-19)\n| num_employees = 11,300 (2018)\n| parent = [[Indian Railways]]\n| homepage = https://icf.indianrailways.gov.in/\n}}\n'''Integral Coach Factory''' (ICF) is a manufacturer of [[ICF coaches|rail coach]]es located in [[Perambur]], [[Chennai]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]. It was established in 1955, and is owned and operated by the [[Indian Railways]]. It is located in [[Perambur]],in the suburbs of Chennai. The ICF is one of the three rake production units of the Indian Railways, the other two being the [[Modern Coach Factory, Raebareli|Modern Coach Factory]] at [[Raebareli]] and the [[Rail Coach Factory]] at [[Kapurthala]].<ref>{{cite news\n | last = Kumar\n | first = S. Vijay\n | coauthors =\n | title = Railways may buy readymade trains from private players\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | pages = 1\n | language =\n | publisher = Kasturi & Sons\n | date = 15 July 2019\n | url = https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/railways-may-buy-readymade-trains-from-private-players/article28430579.ece\n | accessdate = 21 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe coach factory primarily manufactures [[rolling stock]] for Indian Railways but also exports railway coaches to other countries. ICF set a new record producing 2,503 coaches in the fiscal year 2017\u20132018. It became the world's largest railway coach manufacturer, rolling out 3,262 coaches in the fiscal year 2018\u20132019, up from 1,437 coaches in 2009\u20132010,<ref>{{cite news\n | last = Kumar\n | first = S. Vijay\n | title = AIRF opposes move to purchase trains\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | pages = 5\n | language =\n | publisher = Kasturi & Sons\n | date =15 July 2019\n | url = https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/airf-opposes-move-to-purchase-trains/article28430804.ece\n | access-date = 21 July 2019}}</ref> expecting to produce 4,000 units in the fiscal year 2019\u20132020.<ref name=\"Development of Train 19\">{{cite news\n | last = Narasimhan\n | first = T E\n | coauthors =\n | title =  After Train 18, ICF to develop Train 19, sleeper version of Train 18\n | newspaper = Business Standard\n | location = Chennai\n | pages =\n | language =\n | publisher = Express Publications\n | date = 21 May 2019\n | url = https://www.business-standard.com/article/indian-railways/after-train-18-icf-to-develop-train-19-sleeper-version-of-train-18-119052101469_1.html\n | accessdate = 23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nA premier production unit of the Indian railways, the ICF manufactures a range of coaches, including [[Linke-Hofmann-Busch]] (LHB) ones, in addition to self-propelled train sets (SPTs) such as [[electrical multiple unit]]s (EMU).<ref name=\"IE_ICFTestTrack\">{{cite news\n | last = Parthasarathy\n | first = Venkatesan\n | coauthors =\n | title = Padi-Anna Nagar line to turn ICF test track\n | newspaper = The New Indian Express\n | location = Chennai\n | pages =\n | language =\n | publisher = Express Publications\n | date = 2 August 2017\n | url = http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2017/aug/02/padi-anna-nagar-line-to-turn-icf-test-track-1637052.html\n | accessdate = 14 July 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:Chennai Egome-Kollam Junction express at Kollam, Aug 2019.jpg|right|thumb|Utkrisht coaches of [[Chennai Egmore\u2013Kollam Junction Express|Chennai-Kollam Express]], manufactured at ICF, in [[Kollam Junction railway station]]]]\n\n==History==\nThe Integral Coach Factory is one of the earliest production units of independent [[India]]. It was inaugurated by the first [[Prime Minister of India]] [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] on 2 October 1955. Later the Furnishing Division was inaugurated on 2 October 1962 and the production of fully furnished coaches steadily increased over the years. The total estimated cost of the factory was {{INR}} 74.7 million. In full production, about 350 broad-guage coaches per annum are produced.<ref>https://eparlib.nic.in/bitstream/123456789/55733/1/lsd_01_06_23-03-1954.pdf page 4</ref>\n\n==Manufacturing==\nThe ICF consists of two main divisions, namely, shell division and furnishing division. The shell division manufactures the skeleton of the rail coach, while the furnishing division is concerned with the coach interiors and amenities. An ancillary unit to the ICF is being built in [[Haldia]], [[West Bengal]] for furnishing [[diesel multiple units]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/industry-and-economy/logistics/article2854285.ece | title=Railways' Haldia factory phase I may be commissioned by Oct/Nov | work=[[The Hindu]] | date=2 February 2012 | accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref> ICF manufactures more than 170 varieties of coaches including the [[Kolkata Metro rolling stock|Kolkata Metro]] rakes for BHEL, NGEF, Medha, first and second class coaches, pantry and kitchen cars, luggage and brake vans, self-propelled coaches, [[electric multiple unit|electric]] (EMU), diesel (DMU) and mainline electric multiple unit (MEMU), metro coaches and diesel-electric tower cars, accident relief medical vans (ARMV), inspection cars (RA), fuel test cars, track recording cars and luxury coaches. The plant employs about 11,095 people and manufactures about 2000 coaches per year. ICF churned out 1,503 coaches in 2010<ref name=\"ICF_StainlessSteelCoachPlant\">[http://www.steelguru.com/stainless_steel_news/ICF_to_set_up_a_stainless_steel_coaches_manufacturing_plant/222620.html ICF to set up a stainless steel coaches manufacturing plant]</ref> and in August 2011, ICF was sanctioned a project for manufacturing stainless steel shells and high-speed bogies and an increase in capacity from 1,500 to 1,700 coaches.<ref name=\"ICF_StainlessSteelCoachPlant\"/> In 2013\u201314, it built 25 [[LHB Coaches]], 248 air-conditioned and 1185 non-AC coaches.<ref>http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/ICF-produces-record-1622-coaches/articleshow/33089541.cms</ref> It plans to increase its manufacturing capacity of LHB coaches. It has set a target to manufacture 300 LHB coaches in 2014-15 and reach a capacity of 1000 LHB coaches by 2016\u201317. Now, the conventional type of coaches of ICF design has been completely dispensed with and ICF is manufacturing all steel all welded modern LHB coaches fully. ICF has turned out a record outturn of 2277 coaches during the year 2016-17 consisting of more than 50 variants involving high technological inputs, meticulous planning and execution.<ref>http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/asia/indian-government-approves-kolar-coach-factory.html?channel=529</ref> A total of 60,000 coaches had been produced till end of December, 2019, by ICF since its inception. This makes ICF the largest rail coach manufacturer in the world. On an average, the ICF turns out about 10 coaches of various types in a single day.<ref>{{cite news \n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | coauthors = \n  | title = ICF surpasses production target, rolls out 2,500th coach \n  | newspaper = The Hindu\n  | location = Chennai\n  | pages = \n  | language = \n  | publisher = Kasturi & Sons\n  | date = 1 April 2018\n  | url = https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/icf-surpasses-production-target-rolls-out-2500th-coach/article23404214.ece\n  | accessdate = 20 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nICF has also turned out the first semi high speed train set of India, the Train 18, later christened as [[Vande Bharat Express]], which was flagged off by the Prime Minister of India on 15th February, 2019. One more Vande Bharat Express train set manufactured by ICF is now running between New Delhi and Vaishno Devi Katra.\n\n==Exports==\nICF also exports rail cars to various countries.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Export markets\n|-\n|-\n|Africa\n|{{ANG}}<br />{{MOZ}}<br />{{NGR}}<br />{{TAN}}<br />{{UGA}}<br />{{ZAM}}\n|-\n|Asia\n|{{BAN}}<br />{{MYA}}<br />{{ROC}} (Taiwan)<br />{{SRI}}<br />{{THA}}<br />{{NEP}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Prasain |first1=Krishana |title=Janakpur-Jayanagar rail service to resume operations by March |url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/01/16/janakpur-jayanagar-rail-service-to-resume-operations-by-march |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=In May 2018, the Railways Department signed an agreement with the Indian coach manufacturer Integral Coach Factory of Chennai |agency=Kantipur Media Group |publisher=kathmandupost.com |date=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Other==\nA [[Regional Railway Museum (Chennai)|Regional Railway Museum]] is situated in the factory premises. It has a collection of nascent models of trains and models endemic to the [[Indian Railways]]. About 59.1 million units of electricity had been generated through the windmills installed by ICF in [[Tirunelveli district]] in 2011 which met 80 percent of the plant's electrical energy requirements.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/coach-factory-to-use-rs-250-cr-to-upgrade-bogies/462943/ | title=Coach factory to use Rs 250 cr to upgrade bogies | work=Business Standard | date=27 January 2012 | accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-02-23/chennai/28139780_1_cfl-bulbs-surplus-power-windmills | title=Surplus from ICF windmills to power TNEB grid soon | work=[[The Times of India]] | date=23 February 2010 | accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.hindu.com/2009/04/10/stories/2009041054990500.htm | title=Integral Coach Factory installs seven windmills | work=[[The Hindu]] | date=10 April 2009 | accessdate=19 February 2012 | location=Chennai, India}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nThe air-conditioned train-sets manufactured by ICF for [[Kolkata Metro]] allegedly broke down causing disruption of services. According to newspaper reports, the air-conditioned rakes have been sent to Kolkata without conducting dry runs because the ICF does not have third rail testing facilities.<ref>{{cite web|author=(Jayanta) 18 September 2011, 03.51am IST |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-09-18/kolkata/30171837_1_air-conditioned-rake-metro-services-first-ac-rake |title=Snag disrupts Metro services develops snag, commuters stranded|publisher=The Times of India|date=2011-09-18 |accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|agency=TNN |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-08-09/kolkata/29868061_1_metro-services-dum-dumbound-metro-officials |title=Snag disrupts Metro services|publisher=The Times of India|date=2011-08-09 |accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|agency=TNN|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-10-02/kolkata/30234790_1_metro-service-dum-dum-and-maidan-metro-staff |title=Snag hits Metro on Panchami day|publisher=The Times of India|date=2011-10-02 |accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraphindia.com\">{{cite web|author=Sanjay Mandal |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1111031/jsp/calcutta/story_14670772.jsp |title=AC rakes throw Metro off track |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2011-10-31 |accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Jayanta Gupta |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-06-25/kolkata/29702606_1_new-rakes-third-rail-current-collector-metro-ac |title=Metro AC rakes may break down during rains|publisher=The Times of India|date=2011-06-25 |accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thestatesman.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=350330&catid=73 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-04-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130222065349/http://www.thestatesman.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=350330&catid=73 |archivedate=22 February 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Our Special Correspondent |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110917/jsp/calcutta/story_14516111.jsp |title=Snag in AC Metro rake |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2011-09-17 |accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110918/jsp/bengal/story_14521625.jsp |title=2 days in a row, AC rake snags |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2011-09-18 |accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/After-technical-snags-developed-in-an-AC-rake-metro-train-services-were-disrupted-this-morning-Trains-could-not-run-between-Girish-Park-and-Dumdum-They-ran-only-from-Girish-Park-to-New-Garia-/articleshow/10050212.cms |title=After technical snags developed in an AC rake metro train services were disrupted this morning. Trains could not run between Girish Park and Dumdum. They ran only from Girish Park to New Garia.|publisher=The Times of India |date=2011-09-20 |accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://in.news.yahoo.com/ac-rakes-throw-metro-000000249.html |title=AC rakes throw Metro - Yahoo! News India |publisher=In.news.yahoo.com |date=2011-10-31 |accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|India}}\n* [[Diesel Locomotive Factory, Marhowra|Diesel Locomotive Factory]], [[Marhaura|Marhowra]]\n* [[Electric Locomotive Factory, Madhepura|Electric Locomotive Factory]], [[Madhepura]]\n* [[Chittaranjan Locomotive Works]], [[Asansol]]\n* [[Diesel Locomotive Works]], [[Varanasi]]\n* [[Modern Coach Factory, Raebareli|Modern Coach Factory]], [[Raebareli]]\n* [[Rail Coach Factory, Kapurthala|Rail Coach Factory]], [[Kapurthala]]\n* [[Rail Wheel Plant, Bela|Rail Wheel Plant]], [[Bela, Bihar|Bela]]\n* [[Rail Wheel Factory]], [[Yelahanka|Yelehanka]]\n* [[Titagarh Wagons]], [[Titagarh]]\n* [[List of locomotive builders|List of locomotive builders by countries]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.icf.indianrailways.gov.in/}}\n* [http://trainstuff.in/icf-lhb Conventional ICF coaches vs LHB coaches and list of trains using LHB coaches]\n\n{{coord|13.09832|80.20844|type:landmark_region:IN|display=title}}\n\n{{Chennai Topics}}\n{{Indian Railways}}\n{{Railways in Southern India}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2011}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Chennai]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Economy of Chennai]]\n[[Category:Rolling stock manufacturers of India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|A production unit under Ministry of Railways (India)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Integral Coach Factory\n| logo = \n| type = [[Government]]\n| industry = [[Rail transport]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|1955|10|02}}\n| hq_location = [[Chennai]], [[Tamilnadu]], [[India]] \n| area_served = [[Asia-Pacific]] <br /> [[Africa]]\n| key_people = Rahul Jain <br /> (General Manager)\n| products = [[Rolling stock]] <br /> [[Electric multiple unit|EMU]] <br /> [[MEMU]]\n| production = 3262 coaches (2018-19)\n| num_employees = 11,300 (2018)\n| parent = [[Indian Railways]]\n| homepage = https://icf.indianrailways.gov.in/\n}}\n'''Integral Coach Factory''' (ICF) is a manufacturer of [[ICF coaches|rail coach]]es located in [[Perambur]], [[Chennai]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]. It was established in 1955, and is owned and operated by the [[Indian Railways]]. It is located in [[Perambur]],in the suburbs of Chennai. The ICF is one of the three rake production units of the Indian Railways, the other two being the [[Modern Coach Factory, Raebareli|Modern Coach Factory]] at [[Raebareli]] and the [[Rail Coach Factory]] at [[Kapurthala]].<ref>{{cite news\n | last = Kumar\n | first = S. Vijay\n | coauthors =\n | title = Railways may buy readymade trains from private players\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | pages = 1\n | language =\n | publisher = Kasturi & Sons\n | date = 15 July 2019\n | url = https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/railways-may-buy-readymade-trains-from-private-players/article28430579.ece\n | accessdate = 21 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe coach factory primarily manufactures [[rolling stock]] for Indian Railways but also exports railway coaches to other countries. ICF set a new record producing 2,503 coaches in the fiscal year 2017\u20132018. It became the world's largest railway coach manufacturer, rolling out 3,262 coaches in the fiscal year 2018\u20132019, up from 1,437 coaches in 2009\u20132010,<ref>{{cite news\n | last = Kumar\n | first = S. Vijay\n | title = AIRF opposes move to purchase trains\n | newspaper = The Hindu\n | location = Chennai\n | pages = 5\n | language =\n | publisher = Kasturi & Sons\n | date =15 July 2019\n | url = https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/airf-opposes-move-to-purchase-trains/article28430804.ece\n | access-date = 21 July 2019}}</ref> expecting to produce 4,000 units in the fiscal year 2019\u20132020.<ref name=\"Development of Train 19\">{{cite news\n | last = Narasimhan\n | first = T E\n | coauthors =\n | title =  After Train 18, ICF to develop Train 19, sleeper version of Train 18\n | newspaper = Business Standard\n | location = Chennai\n | pages =\n | language =\n | publisher = Express Publications\n | date = 21 May 2019\n | url = https://www.business-standard.com/article/indian-railways/after-train-18-icf-to-develop-train-19-sleeper-version-of-train-18-119052101469_1.html\n | accessdate = 23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nA premier production unit of the Indian railways, the ICF manufactures a range of coaches, including [[Linke-Hofmann-Busch]] (LHB) ones, in addition to self-propelled train sets (SPTs) such as [[electrical multiple unit]]s (EMU).<ref name=\"IE_ICFTestTrack\">{{cite news\n | last = Parthasarathy\n | first = Venkatesan\n | coauthors =\n | title = Padi-Anna Nagar line to turn ICF test track\n | newspaper = The New Indian Express\n | location = Chennai\n | pages =\n | language =\n | publisher = Express Publications\n | date = 2 August 2017\n | url = http://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2017/aug/02/padi-anna-nagar-line-to-turn-icf-test-track-1637052.html\n | accessdate = 14 July 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:Chennai Egome-Kollam Junction express at Kollam, Aug 2019.jpg|right|thumb|Utkrisht coaches of [[Chennai Egmore\u2013Kollam Junction Express|Chennai-Kollam Express]], manufactured at ICF, in [[Kollam Junction railway station]]]]\n\n==History==\nThe Integral Coach Factory is one of the earliest production units of independent [[India]]. It was inaugurated by the first [[Prime Minister of India]] [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] on 2 October 1955. Later the Furnishing Division was inaugurated on 2 October 1962 and the production of fully furnished coaches steadily increased over the years. The total estimated cost of the factory was {{INR}} 74.7 million. In full production, about 350 broad-guage coaches per annum are produced.<ref>https://eparlib.nic.in/bitstream/123456789/55733/1/lsd_01_06_23-03-1954.pdf page 4</ref>\n\n==Manufacturing==\nThe ICF consists of two main divisions, namely, shell division and furnishing division. The shell division manufactures the skeleton of the rail coach, while the furnishing division is concerned with the coach interiors and amenities. An ancillary unit to the ICF is being built in [[Haldia]], [[West Bengal]] for furnishing [[diesel multiple units]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/industry-and-economy/logistics/article2854285.ece | title=Railways' Haldia factory phase I may be commissioned by Oct/Nov | work=[[The Hindu]] | date=2 February 2012 | accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref> ICF manufactures more than 170 varieties of coaches including the [[Kolkata Metro rolling stock|Kolkata Metro]] rakes for BHEL, NGEF, Medha, first and second class coaches, pantry and kitchen cars, luggage and brake vans, self-propelled coaches, [[electric multiple unit|electric]] (EMU), diesel (DMU) and mainline electric multiple unit (MEMU), metro coaches and diesel-electric tower cars, accident relief medical vans (ARMV), inspection cars (RA), fuel test cars, track recording cars and luxury coaches. The plant employs about 11,095 people and manufactures about 2000 coaches per year. ICF churned out 1,503 coaches in 2010<ref name=\"ICF_StainlessSteelCoachPlant\">[http://www.steelguru.com/stainless_steel_news/ICF_to_set_up_a_stainless_steel_coaches_manufacturing_plant/222620.html ICF to set up a stainless steel coaches manufacturing plant]</ref> and in August 2011, ICF was sanctioned a project for manufacturing stainless steel shells and high-speed bogies and an increase in capacity from 1,500 to 1,700 coaches.<ref name=\"ICF_StainlessSteelCoachPlant\"/> In 2013\u201314, it built 25 [[LHB Coaches]], 248 air-conditioned and 1185 non-AC coaches.<ref>http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/ICF-produces-record-1622-coaches/articleshow/33089541.cms</ref> It plans to increase its manufacturing capacity of LHB coaches. It has set a target to manufacture 300 LHB coaches in 2014-15 and reach a capacity of 1000 LHB coaches by 2016\u201317. Now, the conventional type of coaches of ICF design has been completely dispensed with and ICF is manufacturing all steel all welded modern LHB coaches fully. ICF has turned out a record outturn of 2277 coaches during the year 2016-17 consisting of more than 50 variants involving high technological inputs, meticulous planning and execution.<ref>http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/asia/indian-government-approves-kolar-coach-factory.html?channel=529</ref> A total of 60,000 coaches had been produced till end of December, 2019, by ICF since its inception. This makes ICF the largest rail coach manufacturer in the world.  On an average, the ICF turns out about 10 coaches of various types in a single day.<ref>{{cite news \n  | last = \n  | first = \n  | coauthors = \n  | title = ICF surpasses production target, rolls out 2,500th coach \n  | newspaper = The Hindu\n  | location = Chennai\n  | pages = \n  | language = \n  | publisher = Kasturi & Sons\n  | date = 1 April 2018\n  | url = https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/icf-surpasses-production-target-rolls-out-2500th-coach/article23404214.ece\n  | accessdate = 20 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nICF has also turned out the first semi high speed train set of India, the Train 18, which was later christened as [[Vande Bharat Express]], which was flagged off by the Prime Minister of India on 15th February, 2019. One more Vande Bharat Express train set manufactured by ICF is now running between New Delhi and Vaishno Devi Katra.\n\n==Exports==\nICF also exports rail cars to various countries.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Export markets\n|-\n|-\n|Africa\n|{{ANG}}<br />{{MOZ}}<br />{{NGR}}<br />{{TAN}}<br />{{UGA}}<br />{{ZAM}}\n|-\n|Asia\n|{{BAN}}<br />{{MYA}}<br />{{ROC}} (Taiwan)<br />{{SRI}}<br />{{THA}}<br />{{NEP}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Prasain |first1=Krishana |title=Janakpur-Jayanagar rail service to resume operations by March |url=https://kathmandupost.com/money/2020/01/16/janakpur-jayanagar-rail-service-to-resume-operations-by-march |accessdate=7 March 2020 |work=In May 2018, the Railways Department signed an agreement with the Indian coach manufacturer Integral Coach Factory of Chennai |agency=Kantipur Media Group |publisher=kathmandupost.com |date=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\nNow, ICF has undertaken export of Diesel Electric Multiple Unit (DEMUs) as trainsets to Nepal which will be the first BG line in the Mountain Nation.\n\n==Others==\nA [[Regional Railway Museum (Chennai)|Regional Railway Museum]] is situated in the factory premises. It has a collection of nascent models of trains and models endemic to the [[Indian Railways]]. About 59.1 million units of electricity had been generated through the windmills installed by ICF in [[Tirunelveli district]] in 2011 which met 80 percent of the plant's electrical energy requirements.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.business-standard.com/india/news/coach-factory-to-use-rs-250-cr-to-upgrade-bogies/462943/ | title=Coach factory to use Rs 250 cr to upgrade bogies | work=Business Standard | date=27 January 2012 | accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2010-02-23/chennai/28139780_1_cfl-bulbs-surplus-power-windmills | title=Surplus from ICF windmills to power TNEB grid soon | work=[[The Times of India]] | date=23 February 2010 | accessdate=19 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.hindu.com/2009/04/10/stories/2009041054990500.htm | title=Integral Coach Factory installs seven windmills | work=[[The Hindu]] | date=10 April 2009 | accessdate=19 February 2012 | location=Chennai, India}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nThe air-conditioned train-sets manufactured by ICF for [[Kolkata Metro]] allegedly broke down causing disruption of services. According to newspaper reports, the air-conditioned rakes have been sent to Kolkata without conducting dry runs because the ICF does not have third rail testing facilities.<ref>{{cite web|author=(Jayanta) 18 September 2011, 03.51am IST |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-09-18/kolkata/30171837_1_air-conditioned-rake-metro-services-first-ac-rake |title=Snag disrupts Metro services develops snag, commuters stranded|publisher=The Times of India|date=2011-09-18 |accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|agency=TNN |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-08-09/kolkata/29868061_1_metro-services-dum-dumbound-metro-officials |title=Snag disrupts Metro services|publisher=The Times of India|date=2011-08-09 |accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|agency=TNN|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-10-02/kolkata/30234790_1_metro-service-dum-dum-and-maidan-metro-staff |title=Snag hits Metro on Panchami day|publisher=The Times of India|date=2011-10-02 |accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraphindia.com\">{{cite web|author=Sanjay Mandal |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1111031/jsp/calcutta/story_14670772.jsp |title=AC rakes throw Metro off track |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2011-10-31 |accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Jayanta Gupta |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-06-25/kolkata/29702606_1_new-rakes-third-rail-current-collector-metro-ac |title=Metro AC rakes may break down during rains|publisher=The Times of India|date=2011-06-25 |accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thestatesman.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=350330&catid=73 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-04-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130222065349/http://www.thestatesman.net/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=350330&catid=73 |archivedate=22 February 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Our Special Correspondent |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110917/jsp/calcutta/story_14516111.jsp |title=Snag in AC Metro rake |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2011-09-17 |accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1110918/jsp/bengal/story_14521625.jsp |title=2 days in a row, AC rake snags |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=2011-09-18 |accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/After-technical-snags-developed-in-an-AC-rake-metro-train-services-were-disrupted-this-morning-Trains-could-not-run-between-Girish-Park-and-Dumdum-They-ran-only-from-Girish-Park-to-New-Garia-/articleshow/10050212.cms |title=After technical snags developed in an AC rake metro train services were disrupted this morning. Trains could not run between Girish Park and Dumdum. They ran only from Girish Park to New Garia.|publisher=The Times of India |date=2011-09-20 |accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://in.news.yahoo.com/ac-rakes-throw-metro-000000249.html |title=AC rakes throw Metro - Yahoo! News India |publisher=In.news.yahoo.com |date=2011-10-31 |accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref>\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Diesel Locomotive Factory, Marhowra|Diesel Locomotive Factory]], [[Marhaura|Marhowra]]\n* [[Electric Locomotive Factory, Madhepura|Electric Locomotive Factory]], [[Madhepura]]\n* [[Chittaranjan Locomotive Works]], [[Asansol]]\n* [[Diesel Locomotive Works]], [[Varanasi]]\n* [[Modern Coach Factory, Raebareli|Modern Coach Factory]], [[Raebareli]]\n* [[Rail Coach Factory, Kapurthala|Rail Coach Factory]], [[Kapurthala]]\n* [[Rail Wheel Plant, Bela|Rail Wheel Plant]], [[Bela, Bihar|Bela]]\n* [[Rail Wheel Factory]], [[Yelahanka|Yelehanka]]\n* [[Titagarh Wagons]], [[Titagarh]]\n\n[[List of locomotive builders|List of locomotive builders by countries]]{{Portal|India}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.icf.indianrailways.gov.in/}}\n* [http://trainstuff.in/icf-lhb Conventional ICF coaches vs LHB coaches and list of trains using LHB coaches]\n\n{{coord|13.09832|80.20844|type:landmark_region:IN|display=title}}\n\n{{Chennai Topics}}\n{{Indian Railways}}\n{{Railways in Southern India}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2011}}\n\n[[Category:Companies based in Chennai]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Economy of Chennai]]\n[[Category:Rolling stock manufacturers of India]]\n", "name_user": "Vatsmaxed", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor cleanup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral_Coach_Factory"}
{"title_page": "Johnny Yong Bosch", "text_new": "{{Short description|American actor, singer and musician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name            = Johnny Yong Bosch\n|image           = Johnny Yong Bosch.jpg\n|birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1976|1|6|mf=y}}<!-- per bio -->\n|birth_place     = [[Kansas City, Missouri]], U.S.\n|residence       = [[West Hills, Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n|occupation      = Actor, voice actor, martial artist, singer, musician\n|years_active    = 1994\u2013present\n|spouse          = Amy Bosch\n|children        = 2<!--- add only when notable and sourced --->\n|family          = <!--- add only when notable and sourced --->\n|module          = \n|image_caption   = Bosch in 2007\n|birth_name      = John Jay Bosch\n|alias           = Kevin Hatcher\n|background      = group_or_band\n|origin          = \n|genre           = Rock<!-- iTunes classifications -->\n|label           = \n|instrument = Vocals, guitar\n|associated_acts = Eyeshine\n|website = {{URL|eyeshine.net}}\n}}\n'''Johnny Yong Bosch''' (born January 6, 1976)<ref>{{cite web|title=Actors in Spandex - Johnny Yong Bosch|url=http://www.awwman.com/ais/adambio.html|accessdate=19 May 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304054033/http://www.awwman.com/ais/adambio.html|archivedate=March 4, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref> is an American actor, voice actor, martial artist, singer and musician. His first major role was the portrayal of Adam Park, the second Black Power Ranger and later, the Green Zeo Ranger and first Green Turbo Ranger in the ''[[Power Rangers]]'' franchise, which led to roles in some martial arts television and feature films. Bosch is located in Los Angeles and does most of his voice-over work at [[Bang Zoom! Entertainment]], [[Animaze]], [[New Generation Pictures]], [[NYAV Post]], [[Studiopolis]] and on some occasions travels to [[Dallas]] to record shows for [[Funimation]].\n\nIn July 2019, a crowdfunding campaign for the film ''Legend of the White Dragon'', featuring Jason David Frank, Bosch, Jason Faunt, Ciara Hannah, Yoshi Sudarso, Chrysti Ane and Jenna Frank, was launched on [[Kickstarter]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/batinthesun/legend-of-the-white-dragon|title=LEGEND OF THE WHITE DRAGON|website=Kickstarter|language=en|access-date=2019-07-18}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nBosch was born in [[Kansas City, Missouri]] and raised in [[Garland, Texas]], as '''John Jay Bosch'''.<ref name=\"halfkorean\" /><ref name=\"ledger\">{{cite news | title=Meet Johnny Yong Bosch | agency=Universal Press Syndicate | year=1995 | work=[[Mini Page|The Mini Page]] | first=Betty | last=Debnam | via=Lakeland Ledger | publication-date=September 27, 1995 | page=6B }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://senshicon.org/johnny-yong-bosch-is-coming-to-senshi-con/|title=Johnny Yong Bosch is coming to Senshi Con! {{!}} Senshi Con|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref> His father was a soldier in the Army and met his mother while stationed in South Korea. He was interested in martial arts at an early age, inspired by martial arts movies and [[Bruce Lee]].<ref name=\"halfkorean\">{{cite web|url=http://www.halfkorean.com/?page_id=379|title=Interview with Johnny Yong Bosch|author=|date=|work=HalfKorean.com|accessdate=March 4, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ledger\"/> He taught himself martial arts at first,<ref name=\"ledger\"/> mimicking moves from Lee as well as Jackie Chan.<ref name=\"bio\"/> Bosch said he was ridiculed a lot when he was young and became a bully, but made a change for the better after studying kung fu. In addition to training in martial arts, in which he won several competitions, he also played soccer.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.awwman.com/ais/adambio.html|title=Actors in Spandex \u2013 Johnny Yong Bosch|work=awwman.com|accessdate=March 7, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304054033/http://www.awwman.com/ais/adambio.html|archivedate=March 4, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"ledger\"/>\n\n===''Power Rangers''===\nBosch auditioned for the ''[[Power Rangers]]'' show in Dallas after being informed of the audition by his martial arts instructor.<ref name=\"halfkorean\"/> In 1994, he landed the role of Adam Park, the new Black Power Ranger, replacing [[Walter Emanuel Jones]] in the second season of ''[[Mighty Morphin Power Rangers]]''. Bosch said that when he got the part, he changed his middle name to Yong, which was part of his mother's given name, at the request of Saban who thought his credited name needed to be more Asian.<ref name=\"bio\"/> For the feature film ''[[Power Rangers: The Movie]]'',<ref name=\"halfkorean\"/> he did all of his stunts after his stuntman had broken his leg.<ref name=\"bio\"/> He also noted that among all the different animal characters the Rangers got to be associated, his was associated to a frog.<ref name=\"theotaku\"/><ref name=\"dorkshelf\"/> In ''[[Power Rangers Zeo]]'', Bosch's character became a Green Ranger. His final regular stint in the franchise was in ''[[Power Rangers Turbo]]'', where his character passes his Green Turbo Ranger powers to a new member.<ref name=\"halfkorean\"/> He played Park in the second feature film ''[[Turbo: A Power Rangers Movie]]''.<ref name=\"bio\"/><ref name=\"halfkorean\"/> In looking back at his acting for the show, Bosch said that \"Power Rangers was a lot of fun but it was a kid's show and very cheesy because of it, which made getting work after that really hard. Plus, I didn't know squat about acting then.\"<ref name=\"halfkorean\"/> His best friends on the set included [[Jason David Frank]] (who played [[Tommy Oliver]]), [[Jason Narvy]] (who played [[Bulk and Skull|Skull]]) and [[Nakia Burrise]] (who played [[Tanya Sloan]]).<ref name=\"bio\"/> At the request of ''Power Rangers'' director [[Koichi Sakamoto]], he had a guest appearance in the ''[[Power Rangers Operation Overdrive]]'' episode \"Once A Ranger\" in 2007 for the franchise's 15th anniversary, where he mentioned he got to go to New Zealand.<ref name=\"theotaku\"/> He and Narvy also starred in the film ''Wicked Game'', also known as ''Extreme Heist'', which was directed by Sakamoto and features several other ''Power Rangers'' alumni.<ref name=\"wicked\">{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Extreme-Heist-Johnny-Yong-Bosch/dp/B00005V4XY|title=Amazon.com: Extreme Heist: Johnny Yong Bosch, George Cheung, Michael Hexum, Luke LaFontaine, Motoko Nagino, Jason Narvy, Koichi Sakamoto, Paul Schrier, Danny W. Stallcup, Xuyen Valdiva: Movies & TV|author=|date=|work=amazon.com|accessdate=March 7, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"wicked blogspot\">{{cite web|url=http://afterthepower.blogspot.com/2009/03/johnny-yong-bosch-jason-narvy-paul.html|title=Johnny Yong Bosch, Jason Narvy, Paul Schrier, Danny Wayne Stallcup & Ed Neil in \"Wicked Game\" (2002) \u2013 After the Power|author=|date=|work=afterthepower.blogspot.com|accessdate=March 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, a crowdfunding campaign for the film ''Legend Of The White Dragon'', including Jason David Frank, Bosch, Jason Faunt, Ciara Hannah, Yoshi Sudarso, Chrysti Ane and Jenna Frank, was launched on kickstarter.<ref>[https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/batinthesun/legend-of-the-white-dragon Legend of the dragon crowdfunding on www.kickstarter.com]</ref>\n\n===Voice acting===\nBosch made his voice acting debut as main character [[Vash the Stampede]] from ''[[Trigun]].'' In 2006, he worked once again with Koichi Sakamoto on the film ''[[Broken Path]]''. In the same year, Bosch was also cast as the lead role of [[Ichigo Kurosaki]] in the hit shonen anime ''[[Bleach (TV series)|Bleach]]''. In 2007, Bosch co-starred alongside [[Ray Park]] in a comic-book style action film, ''Hellbinders''. Among other works, Bosch also voiced [[Lelouch Lamperouge|Lelouch]] in ''[[Code Geass]]'' in 2008, and [[Izaya Orihara]] in ''[[Durarara]]'' in 2011.\n\nIn video games, Bosch voiced Firion, the protagonist of ''[[Final Fantasy II]]'', in the crossover games ''[[Dissidia: Final Fantasy]]'' and ''[[Dissidia 012 Final Fantasy]].'' In 2011, he voiced Yang in ''[[Super Street Fighter IV Arcade Edition]]'', Tohru Adachi and the protagonist [[Yu Narukami]] in the ''[[Persona 4]]'' games and its [[Persona 4: The Animation|anime adaptation]]. In 2014, Bosch also voiced main character Hajime Hinata from ''[[Danganronpa 2: Goodbye Despair]].'' In 2015, he voiced ''[[Kung Jin]]'' in ''[[Mortal Kombat X]]''. Among video games, Bosch liked voicing Nero in Devil May Cry 4 as he got to travel to Japan to do the motion capture. In the same year, Bosch landed the role of Artemis in [[Viz Media]]'s redub of ''[[Sailor Moon (TV series)|Sailor Moon]]'' as well as ''[[Sailor Moon Crystal]].'' Bosch also voiced lead character Nate Adams from ''[[Yo-kai Watch]]'' which has aired on [[Disney XD]] in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-09-11/yo-kai-watch-anime-october-5-u.s-debut-dub-cast-revealed/.92817|title=Yo-kai Watch Anime's October 5 U.S. Debut, Dub Cast Revealed|author=|date=|work=animenewsnetwork.com|accessdate=October 21, 2016}}</ref> He is also doing the voice dub of Yukimura Sanada in ''[[Samurai Warriors]]'' (all the way to ''[[Samurai Warriors 3]]'') and ''[[Warriors Orochi]]'' series (up to [[Warriors Orochi 2|its sequel]]).\n\nOn July 4, 2017, he voiced Broccoli Punch in Cartoon Network's ''[[Mighty Magiswords]]'', recording with fellow Power Rangers actor [[Paul Schrier]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TVsKyle/status/760619281885396996|title=Good session today!pic.twitter.com/XRWQiSEnlQ|first=Kyle A.|last=Carrozza|date=August 2, 2016}}</ref> He reprised his role as Broccoli Punch, as well as playing the Giant Monster and Whiney, in the second-season two-parter episode \"The Incredible Tiny Warriors\".\n\nIn 2019, Bosch replaced [[Vic Mignogna]] as the new voice of [[Broly]] and [[List of One Piece characters#Sabo|Sabo]] for the [[Funimation]] dub of ''[[Weekly Sh\u014dnen Jump|Shonen Jump]]'''s ''[[Dragon Ball]]'' and ''[[One Piece]]'', respectively, due to the [[Vic Mignogna#Sexual harassment allegations|sexual harassment allegations against Mignogna]].<ref>https://twitter.com/johnnyyongbosch/status/1201905026349723648</ref><ref>https://twitter.com/bmtrocks/status/1184986519725072384</ref>\n\n===Eyeshine===\n[[File:Johnny Yong Bosch by Gage Skidmore.jpg|thumb|right|Bosch performing with Eyeshine at the 2017 Saboten Con]]\nBosch got involved in music by teaching himself how to play guitar. In his band Eyeshine, he provides vocals, songwriting, and guitar. He describes the type of music he plays as \"Edge Rock. We're somewhere on the edge of sounding like grunge, alt. rock, punk and pop.\"<ref name=\"halfkorean\"/> His musical inspirations include [[The Beatles]], [[Foo Fighters]], [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]], [[Led Zeppelin]] and also movie soundtracks.<ref name=\"theotaku\"/>\n\nThe band released an instrumental album called ''Sonosis''. Bosch described the album as \"something you could just listen to and could move you to feel something\" and that \"the titles were a reflection of the emotions we felt as we wrote the songs\".<ref name=\"theotaku\"/>\n\nThe band gave their final performance in [[Yama-Con]] in December 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.knoxnews.com/story/entertainment/2017/11/30/pigeon-forges-yama-con-2017-what-know-before-you-go/875708001/|title=Pigeon Forge's Yama-Con 2017: What to know before you go|last=Jones|first=Maggie|website=Knoxville News Sentinel|language=en|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n\n===Personal life===\nBosch was born to a [[Koreans|Korean]] mother and an American father of Irish and German descent. He is the second of four children in his family.<ref name=\"bio\"/> He has mentioned being a Christian in some of his interviews.<ref name=\"halfkorean\"/><ref name=\"bio\"/><ref name=\"dorkshelf\">{{cite web|url=http://dorkshelf.com/2010/08/30/interview-with-johnny-yong-bosch-of-bleach-and-power-rangers/|title=Interview with Johnny Yong Bosch of Bleach and Power Rangers|author=|date=August 30, 2010|work=Dork Shelf|accessdate=March 4, 2016}}</ref> He is married to Amy Bosch and has a daughter named Novi and a son named Jetson.<ref name=\"halfkorean\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BWX_sahDO3Y/|title=Jet made a new friend. So good seeing old friends at Maurice and Emi's wedding! I'm so mad I forgot to take a family pic|last=Bosch|first=Amy|date=|website=Instagram|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BpIUOAIlWrT/|title=Me and Novi did some serious damage on the sponge bob machine at Chuck E. Cheese.|last=Bosch|first=Amy|date=|website=Instagram|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BG2d_Clw47m/|title=\"Oh the things a dad will do to make his daughter happy. Lol\" [Johnny Yong Bosch is in the photo]|last=Bosch|first=Amy|date=|website=Instagram|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-25}}</ref>\n<!-- NEED SOURCE\nHis father is of German and Irish descent.{{citation needed|date=November 2013|reason=need source for this}}.\n-->\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Voice over roles===\n\n====Anime====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ List of dubbing performances in anime\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Source\n|-\n| {{dts|2000|03|28|format=y}} \n|| ''[[Trigun]]'' || [[Vash the Stampede]] ||\n|<ref name=\"halfkorean\"/><!-- ann 20020302, 20030521 -->\n|-\n| {{dts|2001|09|25|format=y}} \n|| ''[[Gate Keepers]]'' || Reiji Kageyama || ||<ref name=\"ann 20020302\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2002-03-02/sakura-con-guest-announcements|title=Sakura Con Guest Announcements|auth