{"title_page": "Arabella Pollen", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n'''Arabella Pollen''' (born 22 June 1961)<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Weekend birthdays\n|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]\n|pages=42\n|publisher=Guardian Media\n|date=21 June 2014\n|url=\n}}</ref> is an English fashion designer and, as '''Bella Pollen''', journalist and author of five novels published between 1997 and 2011.\n\n==Early life==\nArabella Rosalind Hungerford Pollen (Bella Pollen) is the daughter of [[Peregrine Michael Hungerford Pollen]], a former chairman of [[Sotheby's|Sotheby Parke-Bernet]] auction house,<ref>{{cite book|last=Huda|first=Shireen|title=Pedigree and Panache: A History of the Art Auction in Australia|year=2008|publisher=ANU E Press|location=Canberra, ACT|isbn=9781921313721|page=28|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zGcFObWQnZwC&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> and Patricia Helen Barry.<ref name=npg>{{cite web|title=Arabella ('Bella') Pollen (1961\u2013), Novelist and fashion designer|publisher=National Portrait Gallery|url=http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp10819/arabella-bella-pollen|accessdate=12 February 2011}}</ref> Born in [[Oxford]], she was raised in [[Manhattan]].{{citation needed|date=August 2013}}\n\n==Fashion career==\nIn 1981, Pollen founded the eponymous design company '''Arabella Pollen''', described by ''[[The Independent]]'' as: \"designer of crisp, colourful clothes for the young social set\".<ref name=npg/><ref name=\"independent1\">{{cite web|author=Roger Tredre|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/textiles-giant-axes-designer-fashion-firm-the-demise-of-the-arabella-pollen-concern-has-shocked-the-clothing-industry-roger-tredre-reports-on-the-failure-of-an-ambitious-project-2323945.html|title=Textiles giant axes designer fashion firm: The demise of the Arabella Pollen concern has shocked the clothing industry. Roger Tredre reports on the failure of an ambitious project \u2013 UK \u2013 News|publisher=The Independent|date=20 May 1993|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> Among her private clients were [[Diana, Princess of Wales]], [[Margaux Hemingway]] and [[Marianne Faithfull]].<ref name=people22_18>{{cite journal|title=Dishy Designer Arabella Won't Let a Naughty Photograph Interfere with Her Plans to Pollen-Ate British Fashion |journal=People |volume=22 |issue=18 |date=29 October 1984 |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20089009,00.html |accessdate=12 February 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110210000527/http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0%2C%2C20089009%2C00.html |archivedate=10 February 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Between 1981 and 1994, the company was nominated for eleven major fashion awards.{{which|date=August 2013}}\n\nIn 1984, Arabella Pollen won the contract to design staff uniforms for the newly launched Virgin Atlantic Airways and created suits in the 'Virgin Red' that is still the airline's signature colour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.virgin-atlantic.com/gb/en/the-virgin-experience/fitfoo/our-style/our-crew.html|title=Our crew|publisher=Virgin Atlantic|date=|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Kathy Field Stephen|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/1984/0710/071008.html|title=Virgin Atlantic Airlines: flying to London can be cheap \u2013 and fun, too|publisher=CSMonitor.com|date=|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> In 1990, [[Courtaulds]] acquired a minority share in the company, later increasing this to a majority stake. Arabella Pollen closed in 1994, following Courtaulds' withdrawal.<ref name=npg/><ref name=\"independent1\"/> Pollen continued to advise the textile giant as a design consultant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fashionencyclopedia.com/Pi-Ro/Pollen-Arabella.html|title=Arabella Pollen \u2013 Fashion Designer Encyclopedia \u2013 women, suits, style, new, body, collection, dresses, designs, pants, world, look|publisher=Fashionencyclopedia.com|date=|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Writing career==\nIn 1995, Pollen became a writer, working as '''Bella Pollen'''.<ref name=npg/> Her third book, ''Hunting Unicorns'', became a best seller in 2004.<ref name=telegraph20040625>{{cite news|first=Cassandra|last=Jardine|date=25 June 2004|title=Hard times in a perfect world|work=The Telegraph|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/3619528/Hard-times-in-a-perfect-world.html|accessdate=12 February 2011}}</ref> ''Midnight Cactus'' (2007) was sold to [[Paramount Pictures]]. ''Summer of the Bear'' (2011) was an Oprah summer pick and a Richard and Judy best summer read.<ref name=\"telegraph20040625\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprah.com/book/The-Summer-of-the-Bear-by-Bella-Pollen|title=The Summer of the Bear by Bella Pollen By Bella Pollen \u2013 Book Finder|publisher=Oprah.com|date=1 July 2011|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> Pollen has contributed to numerous magazines and newspapers including ''[[The Times]]'', ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', [[The Spectator]], ''[[The Observer]]'' and ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/author/bella-pollen/|title=Bella Pollen|publisher=The Spectator|date=|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=August 2013}}\n\n==Personal life==\nPollen's first marriage was to art dealer Giacomo Dante Algranti in 1985, with whom she had two children, Jesse and Samuel.<ref name=peerage>{{cite web|title=Arabella Rosalind Hungerford Pollen|work=The Peerage|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p25619.htm|accessdate=12 February 2011}}</ref> In 1995, she married David Macmillan, the grandson of former Prime Minister [[Harold Macmillan]], and director of the book publisher, [[Macmillan Publishers]].<ref name=peerage/><ref>{{cite journal|last=Thomas|first=Tony|title=Life after Kipling and Thomas Hardy|journal=Business Review Weekly|volume=14|issue=34\u201337|page=55|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BLWZAAAAIAAJ&q=David+MacMillan#search_anchor|quote=But director David Macmillan, 35, grandson of prime minister/publisher the late Harold Macmillan...}}</ref> The couple have two children, Finn and Mabel.<ref name=peerage/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Meet Me in the In-Between'' (2018)\n* ''The Summer of the Bear'' (2011)\n* ''Midnight Cactus'' (2007)\n* ''Hunting Unicorns'' (2004)\n* ''B Movies, Blue Love'' (1999)\n* ''All about Men'' (1997)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pollen Baronets]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External sources==\n* [http://www.wmagazine.com/people/celebrities/2008/12/bella_pollen/ short profile]\n* [http://www.bellapollen.com/ author website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pollen, Arabella Rosalind Hungerford}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:English fashion designers]]\n[[Category:English women journalists]]\n[[Category:English women novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English women non-fiction writers]]\n\n\n{{England-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n'''Arabella Pollen''' (born 22 June 1961)<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Weekend birthdays\n|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]\n|pages=42\n|publisher=Guardian Media\n|date=21 June 2014\n|url=\n}}</ref> is an English fashion designer and, as '''Bella Pollen''', journalist and author of five novels published between 1997 and 2011.\n\n==Early life==\nArabella Rosalind Hungerford Pollen (Bella Pollen) is the daughter of [[Peregrine Michael Hungerford Pollen]], a former chairman of [[Sotheby's|Sotheby Parke-Bernet]] auction house,<ref>{{cite book|last=Huda|first=Shireen|title=Pedigree and Panache: A History of the Art Auction in Australia|year=2008|publisher=ANU E Press|location=Canberra, ACT|isbn=9781921313721|page=28|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zGcFObWQnZwC&pg=PA28#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref> and Patricia Helen Barry.<ref name=npg>{{cite web|title=Arabella ('Bella') Pollen (1961\u2013), Novelist and fashion designer|publisher=National Portrait Gallery|url=http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp10819/arabella-bella-pollen|accessdate=12 February 2011}}</ref> Born in [[Oxford]], she was raised in [[Manhattan]].{{citation needed|date=August 2013}}\n\n==Fashion career==\nIn 1981, Pollen founded the eponymous design company '''Arabella Pollen''', described by ''[[The Independent]]'' as: \"designer of crisp, colourful clothes for the young social set\".<ref name=npg/><ref name=\"independent1\">{{cite web|author=Roger Tredre|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/textiles-giant-axes-designer-fashion-firm-the-demise-of-the-arabella-pollen-concern-has-shocked-the-clothing-industry-roger-tredre-reports-on-the-failure-of-an-ambitious-project-2323945.html|title=Textiles giant axes designer fashion firm: The demise of the Arabella Pollen concern has shocked the clothing industry. Roger Tredre reports on the failure of an ambitious project \u2013 UK \u2013 News|publisher=The Independent|date=20 May 1993|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> Among her private clients were [[Diana, Princess of Wales]], [[Margaux Hemingway]] and [[Marianne Faithfull]].<ref name=people22_18>{{cite journal|title=Dishy Designer Arabella Won't Let a Naughty Photograph Interfere with Her Plans to Pollen-Ate British Fashion |journal=People |volume=22 |issue=18 |date=29 October 1984 |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20089009,00.html |accessdate=12 February 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110210000527/http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0%2C%2C20089009%2C00.html |archivedate=10 February 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> Between 1981 and 1994, the company was nominated for eleven major fashion awards.{{which|date=August 2013}}\n\nIn 1984, Arabella Pollen won the contract to design staff uniforms for the newly launched Virgin Atlantic Airways and created suits in the 'Virgin Red' that is still the airline's signature colour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.virgin-atlantic.com/gb/en/the-virgin-experience/fitfoo/our-style/our-crew.html|title=Our crew|publisher=Virgin Atlantic|date=|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Kathy Field Stephen|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/1984/0710/071008.html|title=Virgin Atlantic Airlines: flying to London can be cheap \u2013 and fun, too|publisher=CSMonitor.com|date=|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> In 1990, [[Courtaulds]] acquired a minority share in the company, later increasing this to a majority stake. Arabella Pollen closed in 1994, following Courtaulds' withdrawal.<ref name=npg/><ref name=\"independent1\"/> Pollen continued to advise the textile giant as a design consultant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fashionencyclopedia.com/Pi-Ro/Pollen-Arabella.html|title=Arabella Pollen \u2013 Fashion Designer Encyclopedia \u2013 women, suits, style, new, body, collection, dresses, designs, pants, world, look|publisher=Fashionencyclopedia.com|date=|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Writing career==\nIn 1995, Pollen became a writer, working as '''Bella Pollen'''.<ref name=npg/> Her third book, ''Hunting Unicorns'', became a best seller in 2004.<ref name=telegraph20040625>{{cite news|first=Cassandra|last=Jardine|date=25 June 2004|title=Hard times in a perfect world|work=The Telegraph|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/books/3619528/Hard-times-in-a-perfect-world.html|accessdate=12 February 2011}}</ref> ''Midnight Cactus'' (2007) was sold to [[Paramount Pictures]]. ''Summer of the Bear'' (2011) was an Oprah summer pick and a Richard and Judy best summer read.<ref name=\"telegraph20040625\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprah.com/book/The-Summer-of-the-Bear-by-Bella-Pollen|title=The Summer of the Bear by Bella Pollen By Bella Pollen \u2013 Book Finder|publisher=Oprah.com|date=1 July 2011|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref> Pollen has contributed to numerous magazines and newspapers including ''[[The Times]]'', ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', [[The Spectator]], ''[[The Observer]]'' and ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spectator.co.uk/author/bella-pollen/|title=Bella Pollen|publisher=The Spectator|date=|accessdate=2 February 2014}}</ref>{{citation needed|date=August 2013}}\n\n==Personal life==\nPollen's first marriage was to art dealer Giacomo Dante Algranti in 1985, with whom she had two children, Jesse and Samuel.<ref name=peerage>{{cite web|title=Arabella Rosalind Hungerford Pollen|work=The Peerage|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p25619.htm|accessdate=12 February 2011}}</ref> In 1995, she married David Macmillan, the grandson of former Prime Minister [[Harold Macmillan]], and director of the book publisher, [[Macmillan Publishers]].<ref name=peerage/><ref>{{cite journal|last=Thomas|first=Tony|title=Life after Kipling and Thomas Hardy|journal=Business Review Weekly|volume=14|issue=34\u201337|page=55|url=https://books.google.com/?id=BLWZAAAAIAAJ&q=David+MacMillan#search_anchor|quote=But director David Macmillan, 35, grandson of prime minister/publisher the late Harold Macmillan...}}</ref> The couple have two children, Finn and Mabel.<ref name=peerage/>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Meet Me in the In-Between'' (2018)\n* ''The Summer of the Bear'' (2011)\n* ''Midnight Cactus'' (2007)\n* ''Hunting Unicorns'' (2004)\n* ''B Movies, Blue Love'' (1999)\n* ''All about Men'' (1997)\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pollen Baronets]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External sources==\n* [http://www.wmagazine.com/people/celebrities/2008/12/bella_pollen/ short profile]\n* [http://www.bellapollen.com/ author website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pollen, Arabella Rosalind Hungerford}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women writers]]\n[[Category:English fashion designers]]\n[[Category:English women journalists]]\n[[Category:English women novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English women non-fiction writers]]\n\n\n{{England-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript| Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arabella_Pollen"}
{"title_page": "Gurdwara Gobind Ghat", "text_new": "<br />\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{More footnotes|date=April 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox religious building\n| name                  = Gurudwara Gobind Ghat\n| image                 =  \n| alt                   = \n| caption               = \n| map_type              = India Bihar#India\n| map_caption           = Location in [[Bihar]]##Location in [[India]]\n| religious_affiliation = [[Sikhism]]\n| coordinates           = {{coord|25|36|28.77|N|85|10|3.06|E|region:IN}}\n| other_names           = \n| devanagari            = \n| sanskrit_translit     = \n| tamil                 = \n| marathi               = \n| bengali               = \n| country               = [[India]]\n| state                 = [[Bihar]]\n| district              = \n| location              = [[Patna]]\n| elevation_m           = \n| deity                 = [[Guru]]\n| important_festivals   = \n| architecture          = [[Gurdwara]]\n| number_of_temples     = \n| number_of_monuments   = \n| inscriptions          = \n| date_built            = \n| creator               = unknown\n| website               = unknown\n}}'''Gurudwara Sri Guru Gobind Singh Ghat''', also known as Gurudwara Kangan Ghat<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sikhiwiki.org/index.php/Gurdwara_Kangan_Ghat|title=Gurdwara Kangan Ghat - SikhiWiki, free Sikh encyclopedia.|website=www.sikhiwiki.org|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>, is a place of worship ([[Gurdwara|Gurudwara]]) situated on the bank of river [[Ganges]] about {{convert|650|meter|yards|abbr=on}} away from [[Takht Sri Patna Sahib]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://takhatpatnasahib.in/|title=Takhat Sri Harimandir Ji Patna Sahib|website=takhatpatnasahib.in|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>. It is the place where [[Guru Gobind Singh]] threw his gold [[bangle]] ([[kangan]]) and passed on the knowledge of [[Sri Guru Granth Sahib Ji]] to [[Pandit]] Shiv Dutt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151212051909/http://archimedespress.co.uk/books|title=Archimedespress {{!}} Books|date=2015-12-12|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The [[Sri Guru Granth Sahib Ji]] is believed to have taught him the preaching of the nine [[Sikh gurus]], giving him psychological peace.\n\nThis [[ghat]]  is located near Pata [[Patna Sahib Station]] in the state of Bihar. The ghat (a sacred landmark) is marked by a gateway and the [[Gurudwara]] is located on top of it. Guru Gobind Singh Ji immortalized few places in Patna Saheb, which later on where popularly known as Gurudwaras. Gurudwara Gobind Ghat situated on the bank of river Ganga is hardly 200 yards from Harimandir Saheb. It is also popular as Kangan Ghat where Gobind Rai had thrown his gold bangle. On the same bank, Gobind Rai had blessed mental peace to Pandit Shiv Dutt, a devotee of Sri Ram Chandra. Gurdwara Sri Guru Gobind Singh Ghat- is where the child Gobind used to play with his playmates on the bank of the Ganges. Ghat means a place on the bank, usually paved, for bathing, drawing water or for landing or harboring boats. This ghat about one furlong from Takht Sahib is marked by a gateway over which this Gurdwara is situated in a single room. The river has, however, receded since away to the north.\n\n=== See also ===\n\n*[[Akal Takht]]\n*[[Takht Sri Keshgarh Sahib]]\n*[[Takht Sri Damdama Sahib]]\n*[[Hazur Sahib Nanded]]\n*[[Sri Guru Granth Sahib Ji]]\n\n==Notes==\n* Gurudwara Gobind Ghat is also known as Gurudwara Kangan Ghat.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Sikhism}}\n\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures in Patna]]\n[[Category:Ghats of India]]\n[[Category:Memorials to Guru Gobind Singh]]\n", "text_old": "<br />\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{More footnotes|date=April 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox religious building\n| name                  = Gurudwara Gobind Ghat\n| image                 =  \n| alt                   = \n| caption               = \n| map_type              = India Bihar#India\n| map_caption           = Location in [[Bihar]]##Location in [[India]]\n| religious_affiliation = [[Sikhism]]\n| coordinates           = {{coord|25|36|28.77|N|85|10|3.06|E|region:IN}}\n| other_names           = \n| devanagari            = \n| sanskrit_translit     = \n| tamil                 = \n| marathi               = \n| bengali               = \n| country               = [[India]]\n| state                 = [[Bihar]]\n| district              = \n| location              = [[Patna]]\n| elevation_m           = \n| deity                 = [[Guru]]\n| important_festivals   = \n| architecture          = [[Gurdwara]]\n| number_of_temples     = \n| number_of_monuments   = \n| inscriptions          = \n| date_built            = \n| creator               = unknown\n| website               = unknown\n}}'''Gurdwara Sri Guru Gobind Singh Ghat''', also known as Gurudwara Kangan Ghat<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sikhiwiki.org/index.php/Gurdwara_Kangan_Ghat|title=Gurdwara Kangan Ghat - SikhiWiki, free Sikh encyclopedia.|website=www.sikhiwiki.org|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>, is a place of worship ([[Gurdwara|Gurudwara]]) situated on the bank of river [[Ganges]] about {{convert|650|meter|yards|abbr=on}} away from [[Takht Sri Patna Sahib]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://takhatpatnasahib.in/|title=Takhat Sri Harimandir Ji Patna Sahib|website=takhatpatnasahib.in|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>. It is the place where [[Guru Gobind Singh]] threw his gold [[bangle]] ([[kangan]]) and passed on the knowledge of [[Sri Guru Granth Sahib Ji]] to [[Pandit]] Shiv Dutt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151212051909/http://archimedespress.co.uk/books|title=Archimedespress {{!}} Books|date=2015-12-12|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> The [[Sri Guru Granth Sahib Ji]] is believed to have taught him the preaching of the nine [[Sikh gurus]], giving him psychological peace.\n\nThis [[ghat]]  is located near Pata [[Patna Sahib Station]] in the state of Bihar. The ghat (a sacred landmark) is marked by a gateway and the [[Gurudwara]] is located on top of it. Guru Gobind Singh Ji immortalized few places in Patna Saheb, which later on where popularly known as Gurudwaras. Gurudwara Gobind Ghat situated on the bank of river Ganga is hardly 200 yards from Harimandir Saheb. It is also popular as Kangan Ghat where Gobind Rai had thrown his gold bangle. On the same bank, Gobind Rai had blessed mental peace to Pandit Shiv Dutt, a devotee of Sri Ram Chandra. Gurdwara Sri Guru Gobind Singh Ghat- is where the child Gobind used to play with his playmates on the bank of the Ganges. Ghat means a place on the bank, usually paved, for bathing, drawing water or for landing or harboring boats. This ghat about one furlong from Takht Sahib is marked by a gateway over which this Gurdwara is situated in a single room. The river has, however, receded since away to the north.\n\n=== See also ===\n\n*[[Akal Takht]]\n*[[Takht Sri Keshgarh Sahib]]\n*[[Takht Sri Damdama Sahib]]\n*[[Hazur Sahib Nanded]]\n*[[Sri Guru Granth Sahib Ji]]\n\n==Notes==\n* Gurudwara Gobind Ghat is also known as Gurudwara Kangan Ghat.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Sikhism}}\n\n[[Category:Religious buildings and structures in Patna]]\n[[Category:Ghats of India]]\n[[Category:Memorials to Guru Gobind Singh]]\n", "name_user": "Materialscientist", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Reverted edits bySuper66466(talk) to last version by JesusRahul)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gurdwara_Gobind_Ghat"}
